The article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring April 2010 as National Sexual Assault Awareness Month. The proclamation acknowledges the prevalence of sexual assault in America, from verbal harassment to rape, and emphasizes the need to raise awareness, support victims, and strengthen the response to this crime. It highlights that sexual violence disproportionately affects women, but also affects men, children, and individuals from all backgrounds. The proclamation calls for the protection of victims, the empowerment of survivors to seek assistance, and the provision of necessary resources such as medical attention, mental health services, and advocacy during legal proceedings. It mentions the funding and initiatives in place to combat sexual violence, including the Sexual Assault Services Program and prevention campaigns. The proclamation concludes by urging all Americans to reach out to victims, learn more about sexual assault, and speak out against it.